[Vehicle approaching]

07:49.679 --> 07:52.781
[Brakes squeal]

07:54.148 --> 07:55.507
[Door opens]

07:55.929 --> 07:58.150
♪ ♪

07:58.152 --> 07:59.885
[Engine shuts off]

07:59.887 --> 08:04.054
♪ ♪

08:05.959 --> 08:07.559
[Trunk creaks]

08:07.561 --> 08:11.404
♪ ♪

08:19.406 --> 08:21.334
[Engine starts]

08:21.359 --> 08:24.366
♪ ♪

08:31.118 --> 08:34.125
♪ ♪

08:40.126 --> 08:43.683
♪ ♪

08:45.403 --> 08:47.437
[Keys jingling]

08:47.462 --> 08:49.562
[Engine sputtering]

08:49.564 --> 08:51.332
Come on. Come on!

08:51.357 --> 08:53.333
- [Sputtering continues]
- Come on, baby!

08:53.358 --> 08:54.658
Ohh!

08:54.683 --> 08:56.020
[Sighs]

08:56.566 --> 08:58.266
[Engine starts]

08:58.291 --> 08:59.622
- Yes!
- [Gearshift clicks]

08:59.647 --> 09:02.748
[Engine revs, exhaust pops]

09:02.773 --> 09:04.708
♪ ♪

09:05.246 --> 09:07.372
So come on down to Duke City Recliners

09:07.397 --> 09:08.997
and put your feet up!

09:09.022 --> 09:12.676
Mention this ad and get
10% off your first purchase.

09:13.443 --> 09:15.109
And... cut.

09:15.134 --> 09:16.467
Great! How was that?

09:16.469 --> 09:17.864
- Good for camera.
- Sound was good. Yep.

09:17.889 --> 09:20.530
- Thank you. That was great.
- Hold up. Hold up.

09:20.555 --> 09:22.480
I wanna do one more.

09:22.505 --> 09:23.958
Was that okay?

09:23.983 --> 09:27.093
[Clicks tongue] It was great,
uh, but I just... I want...

09:27.095 --> 09:30.612
I want you to connect
more with the audience.

09:30.637 --> 09:32.809
Like you're talking to a friend.

09:33.372 --> 09:36.152
Look into that lens and see a friend.

09:36.177 --> 09:37.411
Can you do that?

09:37.436 --> 09:39.481
I mean, think of a specific friend.

09:39.506 --> 09:41.442
- Do you see him?
- Yes.

09:41.482 --> 09:42.881
Okay. Who is he?

09:42.883 --> 09:45.245
- My friend Ron.
- Great.

09:45.270 --> 09:48.063
Look into that lens and see Ron.

09:48.088 --> 09:52.157
And just two guys, just
chattin' about chairs.

09:52.159 --> 09:53.714
- [Sighs, sniffles]
- D-don't think about it.

09:53.739 --> 09:54.893
Just throw it away.

09:54.895 --> 09:57.170
Last looks. Roll sound.

10:00.481 --> 10:01.500
Sound speed.

10:01.502 --> 10:03.301
- Camera?
- Cam... camera set.

10:03.303 --> 10:04.903
And...

10:04.905 --> 10:07.645
havin' a conversation
with your good friend Ron.

10:07.670 --> 10:09.536
Just a couple of guys talkin'.

10:09.561 --> 10:11.887
And you got some very exciting news

10:11.912 --> 10:13.311
about the recliners

10:13.313 --> 10:14.926
that you've been dyin'
to share with him.

10:14.951 --> 10:16.982
And... action.

10:17.007 --> 10:18.809
So come on down to Duke City Recliners

10:18.834 --> 10:20.434
and put your feet up!

10:20.459 --> 10:24.156
Mention this ad and get
10% off your first purchase.

10:25.031 --> 10:26.264
And... cut!

10:26.289 --> 10:27.489
Great! That's the one!

10:27.514 --> 10:29.414
Check the gate! How did that feel?!

10:29.439 --> 10:30.856
Good, I guess. What...
what did you think?

10:30.881 --> 10:32.473
Good! So good!

10:32.498 --> 10:34.044
Just very, very...

10:34.069 --> 10:35.926
- just great!
- It was very nice.

10:35.951 --> 10:38.680
Listen, you are on a roll, my friend.

10:38.705 --> 10:40.505
I say we strike while the iron is hot.

10:40.530 --> 10:42.489
Remember that other offer we discussed?

10:42.514 --> 10:44.681
More commercials at the discounted rate?

10:44.706 --> 10:46.144
Got my whole crew here.

10:46.146 --> 10:47.536
We could bang out seven more

10:47.561 --> 10:50.458
and give you a run that'll
make you a household name.

10:50.483 --> 10:53.419
- Waddya say?
- But, Mr. Goodman, I...

10:53.444 --> 10:55.942
love the idea of more commercials,

10:55.945 --> 10:57.534
but I just can't swing it.

10:57.558 --> 11:00.075
- My wife didn't want me to do <i> this</i> one.
- You know what?

11:00.100 --> 11:02.809
They say you gotta spend
money to make money.

11:02.834 --> 11:04.458
And, uh...

11:04.483 --> 11:05.982
[Chuckles]

11:06.007 --> 11:07.965
and I tell ya what...
you got a chance here

11:07.990 --> 11:10.368
to potentially spike
your sales by hundreds...

11:10.370 --> 11:12.426
hell, thousands... of new customers

11:12.451 --> 11:14.973
who'd never even heard
of Duke City Recliners.

11:14.975 --> 11:17.301
- What do ya say?
- Sure, s-sure.

11:17.326 --> 11:19.823
B-but... but like I said... [Sighs]

11:19.848 --> 11:22.380
I only have enough to pay for the one.

11:22.382 --> 11:23.815
[Sighs]

11:23.817 --> 11:25.834
Well, you know what?

11:26.434 --> 11:28.715
I like you, and I wanna help.

11:28.740 --> 11:31.496
So I know we discussed a discounted rate

11:31.529 --> 11:33.737
of $545 per commercial,

11:33.762 --> 11:37.372
but if you sign up right
now for our Elite package...

11:37.397 --> 11:39.870
now, that's seven commercials...

11:39.895 --> 11:42.035
I think we can do the whole thing for...

11:42.863 --> 11:44.248
$500 per commercial.

11:44.272 --> 11:46.410
Now, that is $3,500, all in.

11:46.435 --> 11:49.223
That is the bargain of a lifetime.

11:49.843 --> 11:51.794
[Sighs]

11:55.237 --> 11:56.999
I don't know.

11:57.970 --> 12:00.818
Any chance you could do it on credit?

12:02.056 --> 12:04.360
[Inhales sharply] On credit?

12:05.025 --> 12:07.425
No. No.

12:07.427 --> 12:08.860
I can't.

12:08.862 --> 12:11.495
- I'm sorry.
- Uh, maybe another time.

12:11.520 --> 12:14.169
Uh, let me get your money for this one.

12:25.088 --> 12:27.336
Uh, can we make this easier
and just split it four ways?

12:27.361 --> 12:29.506
"Split it four"... I'll
split <i> you</i> four ways.

12:29.531 --> 12:31.294
Don't they teach you capitalism
in that school of yours?

12:31.319 --> 12:32.857
I'm just sayin', we got expenses, man.

12:32.882 --> 12:34.367
You... expen... you don't have expenses!

12:34.392 --> 12:36.198
<i>I've</i> got expenses! You see this?

12:36.223 --> 12:39.057
This is money I've already spent
on airtime for that commercial.

12:39.059 --> 12:40.471
445 bucks.

12:40.496 --> 12:41.963
You know what that leaves me with?

12:41.988 --> 12:45.184
- $100.
- $104.95!

12:45.209 --> 12:47.868
For writing, directing,
producing, client outreach,

12:47.870 --> 12:49.966
- sales, transpo... all of it!
- I get it.

12:49.991 --> 12:52.597
Yeah. So let's get you in the
editing room and finish this thing,

12:52.622 --> 12:55.522
and I don't want to hear
another word about expenses.

12:55.547 --> 12:57.677
Kim: Okay. Electric.

12:57.679 --> 12:59.810
- Jimmy: [Sighs]
- I paid this month.

12:59.835 --> 13:01.504
Anything else?

13:01.529 --> 13:04.593
I bought a couple reams
of paper for the printer.

13:04.618 --> 13:07.527
Hmm. Paper.

13:08.812 --> 13:10.782
One hundred... sixty-two.

13:10.807 --> 13:12.718
Okay, so...

13:15.106 --> 13:16.919
Mm...

13:17.948 --> 13:21.381
Looks like puts me ahead this month...

13:21.406 --> 13:24.150
$3,172.

13:24.845 --> 13:27.649
All right. And what's it to even me up?

13:27.674 --> 13:30.234
Uh... divided by 2.
[Calculator buttons clicking]

13:30.259 --> 13:32.755
$1,586.

13:34.011 --> 13:35.021
Okay.

13:35.046 --> 13:36.878
[Inhales sharply] One thousand...

13:38.020 --> 13:39.486
five hundred...

13:39.488 --> 13:40.646
[Chuckles] Wow.

13:40.671 --> 13:43.000
Mr. Moneybags, huh?

13:43.025 --> 13:46.852
So this... commercial
thing. It's turning a profit?

13:46.877 --> 13:48.901
It's TV.

13:48.926 --> 13:51.138
How could there <i> not</i> be a profit?

13:54.706 --> 13:56.416
You didn't...

13:56.441 --> 13:59.132
drain your bank account, did you?

13:59.157 --> 14:00.929
[Chuckling] What? No...

14:00.954 --> 14:02.357
- I didn't...
- [Knock on door]

14:02.382 --> 14:04.775
Uh, oh, that's, uh, Chinese food.

14:04.800 --> 14:06.066
I ordered it for us.

14:06.091 --> 14:08.231
- You're workin' late, right?
- Yeah. Right. Thanks.

14:08.256 --> 14:09.757
Oh, uh... wait, here.

14:09.782 --> 14:11.693
No, I got this.

14:15.834 --> 14:18.582
- Hey, hi.
- $24.

14:18.607 --> 14:20.304
[Clears throat]

14:23.303 --> 14:25.469
Here. Keep the change.

14:27.778 --> 14:29.384
A dollar?

14:29.409 --> 14:30.894
Yeah.

14:31.504 --> 14:33.542
We can make it zero.

14:35.486 --> 14:37.744
[Freez's <i> "I.O.U."</i> plays]

14:37.769 --> 14:41.624
♪<i> A-E-A-E-I-O-U-U</i> ♪

14:41.649 --> 14:43.733
[Insects chirping]

14:43.758 --> 14:45.443
[Clattering]

14:45.468 --> 14:46.789
[Door creaks]

14:46.814 --> 14:49.757
[Locks clicking]

14:54.426 --> 14:57.978
[Alarm beeping]

15:01.621 --> 15:04.514
[Locks clicking]

15:04.539 --> 15:06.272
[Beeping continues]

15:06.297 --> 15:08.717
[Keypad beeping]

15:08.750 --> 15:10.504
[Beeping stops]

15:11.025 --> 15:12.310
Ahh!

15:12.335 --> 15:15.010
Geez! What the hell?!

15:15.035 --> 15:17.951
I mean, what the hell?
How'd you get in here?

15:17.953 --> 15:19.646
Relax.

15:19.671 --> 15:21.254
I just want to talk.

15:21.256 --> 15:22.744
Talk? [Chuckles]

15:22.769 --> 15:24.523
You mean, like, apologize?

15:24.548 --> 15:27.527
'Cause that's really the
only talk I want to hear.

15:27.529 --> 15:30.495
I want to do some business. Like before.

15:30.520 --> 15:32.320
[Chuckles] Business?

15:32.345 --> 15:35.894
Is that, like, code for
stealing my baseball cards?

15:35.919 --> 15:38.520
I'm not here for your baseball cards.

15:41.487 --> 15:43.099
I'm here...

15:43.124 --> 15:44.749
for this.

15:53.970 --> 15:56.320
Can you get more of these?

16:05.766 --> 16:08.300
You want me to steal <i> this?</i>

16:08.325 --> 16:10.607
Get a prescription
and go to a pharmacist.

16:10.632 --> 16:13.633
- It'll be cheap.
- I need those capsules empty...

16:13.658 --> 16:15.624
before they're sealed.

16:15.649 --> 16:18.107
With those exact markings.

16:20.716 --> 16:24.484
Well... the place I
work doesn't make these.

16:24.486 --> 16:25.952
But...

16:27.843 --> 16:30.010
But what?

16:32.135 --> 16:36.024
I could probably get
some samples diverted

16:36.049 --> 16:38.203
on an R&D request.

16:39.367 --> 16:40.772
So do it.

16:40.797 --> 16:42.963
Why? I mean, what's the point?

16:42.988 --> 16:45.035
I need them.

16:45.060 --> 16:47.247
[Scoffs lightly] O-kay.

16:48.107 --> 16:51.511
And if I don't get them?

16:51.513 --> 16:52.916
Then what?

16:52.941 --> 16:55.408
Are you gonna threaten me?

16:55.433 --> 16:57.404
Break my legs?

17:00.021 --> 17:01.632
You get me those pills,

17:01.657 --> 17:05.026
and I'm gonna pay you $20,000.

17:08.964 --> 17:10.598
Get them.

17:10.624 --> 17:14.827
[Insects chirping]

17:31.063 --> 17:32.772
[Door creaks]

17:33.393 --> 17:35.212
[Sighs]

17:46.005 --> 17:48.899
[Creaking]

17:52.684 --> 17:54.372
[Thud]

17:55.221 --> 17:56.929
[Thud]

18:11.845 --> 18:13.114
[Children shouting in distance]

18:13.139 --> 18:15.005
Woman: Let her have the ball.

18:15.007 --> 18:16.579
[Chatter]

18:16.604 --> 18:18.533
Man: Hold on, okay?

18:18.558 --> 18:20.181
Stacey: Hey, Pop.

18:20.206 --> 18:22.023
You doing okay?

18:22.048 --> 18:24.340
Uh, yeah. It's coming along.

18:24.365 --> 18:26.617
Have a couple of volunteers
here who want to help.

18:26.619 --> 18:28.452
Well, thanks, but I think I'm good.

18:28.454 --> 18:30.929
Please, we can't let you
do it all by yourself.

18:30.954 --> 18:33.087
Certainly not after you
bought all the supplies.

18:33.089 --> 18:35.523
At least let the church reimburse you.

18:35.525 --> 18:37.592
- It's a donation.
- Woman: C'mon.

18:37.594 --> 18:40.181
You've got unskilled but eager laborers.

18:40.206 --> 18:41.674
Let us do <i> something.</i>

18:41.699 --> 18:44.999
Just point and tell us what to do.

18:45.033 --> 18:46.448
Oh.

18:48.850 --> 18:50.816
All right, uh...

18:52.649 --> 18:54.628
how about you dump one of those packs

18:54.653 --> 18:55.965
into the wheelbarrow?

18:55.990 --> 18:59.264
And you... you fill that bucket
up to the brim with water.

18:59.289 --> 19:01.616
And then you dump it
in, little by little,

19:01.618 --> 19:03.909
while he stirs it with a hoe.

19:03.934 --> 19:05.809
- You got it.
- Okay.

19:10.908 --> 19:13.330
I'm ready. What can I do?

19:14.351 --> 19:16.604
- I think we're covered.
- [Chuckles]

19:16.629 --> 19:18.199
You're kidding, right?

19:18.201 --> 19:20.235
It's not that big a job.

19:20.237 --> 19:23.204
[Water splashing]

19:31.361 --> 19:33.877
- Am I doing this right?
- Uh...

19:34.821 --> 19:37.566
why don't you try using this instead?

19:39.250 --> 19:40.891
Excuse me?

19:40.916 --> 19:43.035
It's for the walkway.

19:43.313 --> 19:44.879
Look.

19:45.822 --> 19:48.139
It puts down a texture

19:48.164 --> 19:50.932
so the kids don't slip when it gets wet.

19:50.934 --> 19:54.302
[Chatter in distance]

20:02.001 --> 20:03.534
Like this?

20:03.559 --> 20:05.284
You got it.

20:05.691 --> 20:07.515
Nice and gentle.

20:07.540 --> 20:09.529
- You're Kaylee's Pop-Pop, right?
- [Laughter]

20:09.554 --> 20:10.718
I am.

20:10.743 --> 20:13.400
I am the very proud grandfather.

20:14.386 --> 20:17.199
- I'm Anita.
- Mike.

20:17.224 --> 20:20.180
- Nice to meet you, Mike.
- And you.

20:20.205 --> 20:21.821
And thanks for helping.

20:21.846 --> 20:25.561
Well, thank you for not trying
to do this all by yourself.

20:25.586 --> 20:28.954
[Chatter continues]

20:36.813 --> 20:38.496
[Car door creaks]

20:39.961 --> 20:43.329
[Insects chirping]

20:45.197 --> 20:48.071
[Vehicle passing in distance]

21:00.360 --> 21:02.470
Hey. Carl?

21:02.495 --> 21:03.884
Yeah.

21:04.507 --> 21:07.295
Hold the fort for a
few minutes, wouldja?

21:07.320 --> 21:09.327
You got it, Mike. [Sighs]

21:12.353 --> 21:16.532
[Video game plays <i>"Trojan
Warrior Theme"</i> ]

21:21.349 --> 21:23.519
Oh, hey.

21:24.717 --> 21:25.927
You're here.

21:25.929 --> 21:27.862
This your idea of stealth?

21:28.511 --> 21:31.199
I never claimed to be good
at this. <i>Any</i> of it.

21:31.201 --> 21:32.964
- [Siren wails in distance]
- On that, we can agree.

21:32.989 --> 21:35.290
Yeah, I know. That's why I'm here.

21:35.315 --> 21:37.115
I wanna hire you again.

21:37.140 --> 21:38.539
Do what now?

21:38.541 --> 21:40.542
Hire you. As my back-up man.

21:40.567 --> 21:42.973
Same terms as before.

21:42.998 --> 21:45.146
I don't wanna make the
same mistake as last time.

21:45.148 --> 21:47.201
You don't wanna make the same mistake,

21:47.226 --> 21:48.783
then don't get involved

21:48.785 --> 21:51.119
with whatever it is you're
getting involved <i> with.</i>

21:51.121 --> 21:54.389
But... I'm involved already.

21:54.391 --> 21:55.950
I'm not.

21:55.975 --> 21:57.539
Well...

21:58.664 --> 22:00.881
it's Nacho Varga.

22:05.802 --> 22:07.868
[Sighs]

22:08.972 --> 22:10.578
What about him?

22:10.603 --> 22:12.374
He broke into my house.

22:12.399 --> 22:14.335
He was inside, waiting for me.

22:14.360 --> 22:16.894
Somehow, he got past my security system.

22:16.919 --> 22:18.850
I have no idea how!

22:18.875 --> 22:21.706
All he had to do was
unplug your phone lines.

22:21.731 --> 22:24.249
Oh. That's it?

22:24.274 --> 22:25.530
Huh.

22:25.555 --> 22:27.188
What'd he want?

22:27.190 --> 22:29.986
Pills. Well... not exactly.

22:30.011 --> 22:32.330
Empty Lydristel capsules.

22:32.395 --> 22:36.158
- Lydristel?
- Yeah. They're like nitroglycerin.

22:36.183 --> 22:39.604
And he offered me
money... lots of money.

22:39.629 --> 22:42.370
Way more than they're even worth.

22:42.372 --> 22:44.005
But...

22:44.007 --> 22:48.372
I'm afraid if I don't do it,
or even if I <i> do</i> do it...

22:49.045 --> 22:50.670
I don't know...

22:50.672 --> 22:52.851
Tell him you can't get what he needs.

22:52.876 --> 22:54.492
I already ordered them.

22:54.517 --> 22:57.313
I mean, the shipment gets
here in two days. He knows.

22:57.338 --> 22:59.544
Then make up an excuse.

23:00.719 --> 23:03.151
[Sighs] Fine. $3,000.

23:03.176 --> 23:05.372
- I'll give you $3,000.
- I'm not interested.

23:05.397 --> 23:07.887
And <i> you</i> find a way out of it.

23:07.889 --> 23:09.222
[Scoffs] But...

23:09.224 --> 23:11.058
Not interested!

23:22.756 --> 23:24.501
[Gearshift clicks]

23:25.605 --> 23:26.871
[Seatbelt clicks]

23:26.896 --> 23:28.195
[Engine shuts off]

23:33.813 --> 23:35.916
[Engine starts in distance]

23:38.887 --> 23:41.087
[Cellphone beeping]

23:41.112 --> 23:43.987
_

23:54.135 --> 23:56.269
[Sighs]

24:02.076 --> 24:04.476
- [Alarm beeping]
- [Gasps]

24:05.769 --> 24:07.680
- Paige: Look... full disclosure.
- [Beeping stops]

24:07.682 --> 24:09.944
When you told us about
the disciplinary hearing,

24:09.969 --> 24:11.898
- I admit it... I had concerns.
- [Elevator bell dings]

24:11.942 --> 24:14.259
So, just so you know, I
had to do my due diligence.

24:14.284 --> 24:15.960
I read the transcripts.

24:15.985 --> 24:17.518
All of them.

24:17.520 --> 24:18.953
It was amazing.

24:18.955 --> 24:20.288
What you did to Charles...

24:20.290 --> 24:22.590
you and James set him up perfectly.

24:22.592 --> 24:24.903
[Chuckling] You <i> destroyed</i> him.

24:24.928 --> 24:26.294
Oh, my God.

24:26.296 --> 24:27.929
I couldn't believe some of it.

24:27.931 --> 24:29.884
"I'm not crazy. It's 1216,

24:29.909 --> 24:31.299
- "one after Magna Carta."
- [Elevator bell dings]

24:31.324 --> 24:34.360
- [Laughing] The Magna Carta?
- [Chuckles]

24:34.385 --> 24:36.481
It was perfect.

24:36.506 --> 24:39.507
[Chuckling] "You think
this chicanery is bad?"

24:39.509 --> 24:42.109
Who talks like that? [Chuckles]

24:42.111 --> 24:45.597
On page 5 is a breakdown

24:45.622 --> 24:48.278
of loan-to-deposit ratios
by county, and you can see,

24:48.303 --> 24:50.518
if Mesa Verde is going to
comply with Section 109,

24:50.520 --> 24:52.520
you will have to raise
your loan numbers.

24:52.522 --> 24:54.555
Mm. That can't be right.

24:54.557 --> 24:56.743
We were fine in Arizona.

24:56.768 --> 25:00.526
Yes, but the FDIC requirements
in Utah are different.

25:01.297 --> 25:02.809
96%?

25:02.834 --> 25:04.816
Is it really that high?

25:04.841 --> 25:08.213
I thought Arizona was only 79%.

25:08.238 --> 25:09.871
Again, it was,

25:09.873 --> 25:13.252
but Utah has a higher
loan-to-deposit ratio.

25:14.013 --> 25:16.117
[Sighs]

25:16.145 --> 25:17.887
I think we're gonna need to check that.

25:17.912 --> 25:20.124
That number seems way off.

25:20.149 --> 25:22.149
The numbers are right.

25:22.151 --> 25:24.017
But you can review the
guidelines if you want.

25:24.042 --> 25:25.219
Right here.

25:25.221 --> 25:26.721
[Papers thud]

25:29.050 --> 25:31.742
You gonna check 'em or can we move on?

25:35.318 --> 25:36.976
Uh...

25:39.174 --> 25:40.552
no...

25:41.189 --> 25:44.528
of course, if it's 96%, it's 96%.

25:45.091 --> 25:47.419
We'll increase our loan numbers.

25:47.444 --> 25:49.233
Absolutely.

25:50.380 --> 25:51.679
[Sighs]

25:51.681 --> 25:53.714
Can we review these
fixed mortgage rates?

25:53.716 --> 25:55.240
'Cause that's... [Sighs]

25:55.265 --> 25:57.132
definitely an area we're
gonna need to focus...

25:57.157 --> 25:59.302
- Paige, I'm s... that was...
- ... our attention...

26:00.590 --> 26:02.454
unprofessional.

26:02.479 --> 26:04.632
I didn't mean to speak to you that way.

26:04.657 --> 26:07.359
Kim. Don't worry.

26:07.384 --> 26:09.762
It's not a problem. At all.

26:09.787 --> 26:12.479
No, I'm sorry. There's no excuse
for talking to you like that.

26:12.504 --> 26:13.903
[Sighs]

26:14.867 --> 26:17.805
I know how hard you've
been working on this.

26:17.807 --> 26:19.607
Please, I've forgotten about it already.

26:19.609 --> 26:21.409
You should, too.

26:21.411 --> 26:22.966
Okay?

26:33.109 --> 26:35.829
As far as I'm concerned, all we did...

26:38.465 --> 26:41.671
all we did was tear down a sick man.

26:51.908 --> 26:54.303
Fixed mortgage rates.

26:54.328 --> 26:56.561
I think it's page 3.

26:56.586 --> 26:58.286
- Yes.
- Yeah.

26:59.649 --> 27:02.314
There's an acquisition
comparison at the top,

27:02.339 --> 27:03.950
and you want to go by total...

27:04.360 --> 27:06.808
[Vehicle approaching]

27:06.816 --> 27:08.383
[Brakes squeal]

27:08.386 --> 27:09.993
[Gearshift clicks]

27:10.018 --> 27:13.524
♪ ♪

27:18.896 --> 27:22.403
♪ ♪

27:27.083 --> 27:29.748
[Wheelchair squeaking]

27:29.773 --> 27:31.806
[Tires screeching]

27:31.831 --> 27:35.675
[Engine revs]

27:35.700 --> 27:37.185
[Tires screeching]

27:37.210 --> 27:38.781
- Get in!
- Yeah.

27:38.783 --> 27:39.911
Go! Chop-chop!

27:39.936 --> 27:41.469
C'mon, c'mon!

27:50.773 --> 27:52.436
[Grunts]

28:03.783 --> 28:05.115
Oh.

28:05.140 --> 28:06.282
Get in!

28:06.307 --> 28:07.324
- Let's go.
- Trying.

28:07.349 --> 28:08.747
[Sighs]

28:10.144 --> 28:12.515
[Engine sputtering]

28:12.540 --> 28:13.873
That doesn't sound good.

28:13.898 --> 28:15.761
C'mon, c'mon.

28:16.889 --> 28:18.756
- I think you're flooding it.
- I'm not flooding it!

28:18.781 --> 28:19.858
You're over-cranking it.

28:19.883 --> 28:21.871
Oh, you don't know what
you're talking about!

28:21.896 --> 28:24.230
We're still getting paid
whether we get there or not.

28:24.255 --> 28:26.551
- Maybe we should catch the bus.
- Sh... come on!

28:26.576 --> 28:28.743
Just... it's gonna start, okay?

28:28.768 --> 28:30.902
- [Sputtering continues]
- Yeah, you definitely flooded it.

28:30.927 --> 28:32.546
He drained the battery.
You drained the battery.

28:32.571 --> 28:33.738
Can you not talk about something

28:33.763 --> 28:35.448
you know absolutely nothing about?

28:35.473 --> 28:37.410
- There's a bus we could get in.
- Shh! Shh!

28:37.435 --> 28:39.875
I just need to think for one minute!

28:39.900 --> 28:41.533
[Sighs]

28:42.069 --> 28:44.007
Look, we're taking the bus.

28:44.032 --> 28:45.331
Yeah.

28:46.550 --> 28:48.087
[Grunts]

28:49.425 --> 28:50.865
[Trunk creaks]

28:52.564 --> 28:55.135
[Panting]

28:55.160 --> 28:56.848
Film crew!

28:56.873 --> 28:58.556
Hold up the bus!

29:00.110 --> 29:01.325
You see that?

29:01.350 --> 29:03.699
Fender Stratocaster,
signed by Ritchie Blackmore.

29:03.701 --> 29:06.533
- You know who <i> that</i> is, right?
- Someone no one's ever heard of?

29:06.959 --> 29:08.292
That's real good.

29:08.317 --> 29:09.945
I hope your parents enjoy supporting you

29:09.970 --> 29:11.551
for the rest of their lives.

29:11.961 --> 29:14.511
C'mon, Ritchie Blackmore.

29:14.536 --> 29:16.088
Deep Purple.

29:16.113 --> 29:18.353
Ohh. "Another Brick in the Wall."

29:18.709 --> 29:21.109
Oh, I weep for the future.

29:21.134 --> 29:22.338
[Sighs]

29:22.363 --> 29:25.541
Mr. McGill, we have a problem.

29:25.566 --> 29:27.138
Them.

29:29.452 --> 29:31.088
Hey, fellas. Uh, you ready?

29:31.113 --> 29:32.421
We got the first shot all lined up.

29:32.446 --> 29:34.661
- Can I walk you through it?
- Uh...

29:34.686 --> 29:36.092
We hate to do this to you, but...

29:36.117 --> 29:37.717
- We're having second thoughts.
- Yeah.

29:37.763 --> 29:40.225
I get it. That's just
nerves. Just stage fright.

29:40.250 --> 29:42.581
Uh, tell you what... we got cue cards,

29:42.623 --> 29:44.175
and with the magic of editing,

29:44.200 --> 29:45.937
we're gonna make you guys look like...

29:45.962 --> 29:47.762
James Garner and Mariette Hartley.

29:47.787 --> 29:48.905
It's not that.

29:48.930 --> 29:50.242
It's just that it...

29:50.267 --> 29:51.744
it seems like too much money...

29:51.769 --> 29:53.306
For not a whole lot of return.

29:53.331 --> 29:55.641
And that, my friends... that
is where you're mistaken,

29:55.666 --> 29:58.226
because this is about brand awareness.

29:58.251 --> 30:00.926
From now on, when people think guitars,

30:00.951 --> 30:03.351
they're gonna think "ABQ In Tune."

30:03.376 --> 30:06.377
When they think pianos... "ABQ In Tune."

30:06.379 --> 30:08.579
Drums, xylophones...
for less than the price

30:08.581 --> 30:11.182
of that Ritchie Blackmore
beauty you got on that rack,

30:11.184 --> 30:14.185
you're gonna have the whole
town thinking, "ABQ In Tune."

30:14.187 --> 30:16.030
Yeah, but... but what
about the time slot?

30:16.055 --> 30:17.634
I mean, "Murder, She Wrote" repeats?

30:17.659 --> 30:18.834
- Come on.
- Come on.

30:18.859 --> 30:22.079
Hey, grandmas love
buying the gift of music

30:22.104 --> 30:24.671
for little Johnny and
Sally and Skip, hmm?

30:24.696 --> 30:27.410
And it's school-recital season, so...

30:27.435 --> 30:29.223
where are the kids gonna
get those recorders?

30:29.248 --> 30:31.314
Uh, we don't sell recorders.

30:31.339 --> 30:33.321
Synthesizers, then. But the point is,

30:33.346 --> 30:34.779
those Social Security checks...

30:34.804 --> 30:36.849
they got to be spent somewhere.

30:36.874 --> 30:38.140
Mnh.

30:38.165 --> 30:39.519
Hey, uh... [Clears throat]

30:39.544 --> 30:41.194
as it happens, uh, today only,

30:41.219 --> 30:45.221
I can, uh, offer the
same package, but...

30:45.246 --> 30:47.227
50% off.

30:49.357 --> 30:50.823
Look...

30:50.825 --> 30:52.496
I'm sorry, but we can't.

30:52.521 --> 30:54.224
Not today, guys.

30:54.249 --> 30:56.255
Don't do that. Guys. Now, come on.

30:56.280 --> 30:58.391
Look, I know you want
this. I <i> know</i> you do.

30:58.416 --> 30:59.545
50% off!

30:59.570 --> 31:02.539
Yeah, we get it, but we're just not...

31:02.564 --> 31:04.006
Convinced.

31:05.080 --> 31:06.645
[Sighs]

31:07.356 --> 31:08.867
Free.

31:08.892 --> 31:11.637
[Clears throat] I'll
shoot the spot for free.

31:12.876 --> 31:14.342
For free?

31:14.367 --> 31:16.611
You will shoot this spot for free?

31:16.636 --> 31:19.738
I'll film your ad, and
I'll put it on the air.

31:19.763 --> 31:22.364
But when you see more
traffic coming through here...

31:22.418 --> 31:23.763
and you <i> will...</i>

31:23.788 --> 31:27.782
then we do the other spots
for the original rate.

31:27.807 --> 31:29.492
Okay? Now, how can you say no?

31:29.517 --> 31:30.621
[Sighs]

31:30.646 --> 31:33.156
- I mean, when he puts it like that...
- I guess we can't.

31:33.181 --> 31:34.580
Good.

31:34.605 --> 31:36.333
That's the best decision
you're gonna make.

31:36.358 --> 31:38.347
The... the best!

31:38.372 --> 31:40.656
[Vehicles passing]

31:43.745 --> 31:47.113
[Wind whistling]

32:10.905 --> 32:13.239
[Sighs]

32:15.483 --> 32:16.993
Uh...

32:17.018 --> 32:19.285
you gonna catch the bus, Mr. McGill?

32:20.031 --> 32:22.298
No, I... um...

32:22.323 --> 32:24.875
You guys... get to the editing room.

32:24.900 --> 32:26.689
I just need t...

32:27.617 --> 32:29.146
to sit.

32:45.993 --> 32:47.852
Mr. McGill?

32:49.177 --> 32:52.001
Oh, no. I-I can't.

32:52.026 --> 32:53.659
It's okay.

32:54.756 --> 32:56.107
No, that's yours.

32:56.132 --> 32:57.982
You earned it.

32:58.709 --> 33:00.769
But you're losing money.

33:01.660 --> 33:03.392
We'll see.

33:03.417 --> 33:05.500
It... it'll be fine.

33:07.429 --> 33:09.214
Okay.

33:20.176 --> 33:23.738
So, I finally got my act together.

33:24.675 --> 33:27.965
I pulled a bunch of Alan's
boxes out of the closet.

33:27.990 --> 33:29.554
[Inhales sharply]

33:29.579 --> 33:31.958
Only took me eight years.

33:35.285 --> 33:38.497
I gave all of Alan's clothes a last wash

33:38.523 --> 33:41.157
before driving them over to Goodwill.

33:43.129 --> 33:44.649
I cried.

33:44.868 --> 33:46.386
I cried when I washed them.

33:46.411 --> 33:48.567
I cried when I folded them.

33:48.592 --> 33:50.726
I cried when I dropped 'em off.

33:52.737 --> 33:54.711
But once it was done...

33:55.843 --> 33:57.697
it felt good...

33:58.487 --> 34:00.479
to let them go.

34:00.481 --> 34:02.214
[Man coughs softly]

34:02.216 --> 34:04.833
I kept his uniform, though. [Chuckles]

34:04.858 --> 34:06.403
Can't let <i> that</i> go.

34:06.428 --> 34:09.772
Lord, he'd never forgive me if
I let <i> that</i> go. [Laughs]

34:12.418 --> 34:15.536
But I figure it's okay
to keep one thing, right?

34:15.569 --> 34:17.193
I mean...

34:17.849 --> 34:20.882
people can use the other clothes, but...

34:22.210 --> 34:25.737
not sure what use they'd
have for an old uniform.

34:25.739 --> 34:29.041
[Vehicles passing in distance]

34:29.789 --> 34:31.690
I just don't remember this much homework

34:31.715 --> 34:33.426
when I was Kaylee's age.

34:33.451 --> 34:36.647
It doesn't seem to
bother her, but still...

34:36.672 --> 34:39.417
Most of it's just busywork.

34:39.442 --> 34:42.306
A couple of us actually
spoke to the school board,

34:42.331 --> 34:43.773
and they agreed...

34:43.797 --> 34:45.891
Done. All yours.

34:45.917 --> 34:48.130
Fair warning, the coffee's not all that.

34:48.156 --> 34:49.487
[Chuckles] Mm.

34:49.513 --> 34:51.554
I guess they feel if you can face this,

34:51.580 --> 34:54.014
- you can face anything.
- Could be.

34:54.039 --> 34:57.593
- I must be stronger than I think.
- Mm.

34:57.618 --> 34:58.855
You mind if I ask...

34:58.880 --> 35:00.475
and I really don't mean to pry, but...

35:00.500 --> 35:01.639
Let me guess.

35:01.664 --> 35:04.231
You have another construction
job you need my help on.

35:04.256 --> 35:05.544
Uh, no.

35:05.569 --> 35:08.157
But if I do, you'll be
the first person I call.

35:08.182 --> 35:10.778
[Chuckles] Okay, ask away.

35:12.107 --> 35:14.971
You said you kept
your husband's uniform.

35:15.393 --> 35:17.193
Was he on the job?

35:17.255 --> 35:19.034
On the job?

35:19.060 --> 35:21.308
Oh, you mean the police.

35:21.586 --> 35:22.966
[Chuckling] No.

35:22.991 --> 35:24.758
Alan was a Navy man.

35:24.783 --> 35:27.584
He was well out of the
service when I lost him.

35:28.275 --> 35:29.641
I'm sorry.

35:29.666 --> 35:32.481
The group has heard
my story over and over.

35:32.506 --> 35:35.119
Well, that's what we're here for.

35:39.380 --> 35:41.173
Well...

35:41.198 --> 35:43.705
Alan loved to hike.

35:43.730 --> 35:46.473
We even opened a camping-supply store.

35:46.498 --> 35:49.277
I helped him with the
mail-order side of it.

35:49.302 --> 35:51.201
And then, uh...

35:52.475 --> 35:54.627
this was eight years ago...

35:55.184 --> 35:57.745
he went hiking in Gila National

35:57.770 --> 35:59.741
and never came back.

35:59.766 --> 36:01.666
They found our car,

36:01.691 --> 36:03.613
but they never found him.

36:04.033 --> 36:05.870
And I don't know if...

36:05.895 --> 36:08.048
he slipped and fell
or had a heart attack

36:08.073 --> 36:10.814
or met someone who didn't
like the way he looked...

36:11.474 --> 36:13.140
I don't know.

36:13.165 --> 36:15.996
And even after all these years,

36:16.569 --> 36:20.605
not knowing how he
passed or where he is...

36:24.525 --> 36:26.732
I wish it didn't matter.

36:26.757 --> 36:28.755
But it does.

36:33.117 --> 36:36.619
[Insects chirping]

36:36.644 --> 36:39.788
[Vehicles passing in distance]

36:52.015 --> 36:55.383
[Cellphone dialing]

37:01.943 --> 37:03.551
Pryce: Hello?

37:04.136 --> 37:05.802
It's me.

37:05.827 --> 37:07.848
You make the deal?

37:08.273 --> 37:10.340
Uhhh, no.

37:10.365 --> 37:12.023
Not yet.

37:12.709 --> 37:14.075
Why?

37:15.156 --> 37:16.624
I'm in.

37:18.323 --> 37:20.858
[Insects chirping]

37:20.859 --> 37:23.947
[Vehicles passing in distance]

37:27.915 --> 37:31.206
[Leaves rustling]

37:34.513 --> 37:36.258
[Door closes]

37:36.300 --> 37:38.605
[Groans, sighs]

37:51.923 --> 37:53.664
[Sighs]

37:56.536 --> 37:58.483
[Sighs]

37:58.508 --> 38:01.910
[Vehicles passing in distance]

38:01.912 --> 38:03.711
[Chuckles]

38:04.966 --> 38:07.216
Hey, let's get outta here.

38:07.218 --> 38:08.872
[Scoffs] What?

38:08.897 --> 38:10.330
Get out where?

38:10.355 --> 38:13.882
I am up to my neck in
Mesa Verde. I can't.

38:13.907 --> 38:16.409
- C'mon, we're going. Up.
- No, I can't.

38:16.434 --> 38:18.734
- Na-ah! Nope. Nothing...
- Jimmy... [Laughs]

38:18.759 --> 38:20.759
nothing you can do to stop this.

38:20.761 --> 38:22.606
[Inhales sharply] Uh, one thing...

38:22.631 --> 38:24.055
you have to drive.

38:24.080 --> 38:25.579
[Kruder & Dorfmeister's
<i>"Black Baby"</i> plays]

38:25.604 --> 38:26.833
Oh, oh, oh.

38:26.858 --> 38:28.352
Lookit this guy.

38:28.963 --> 38:30.329
Ohh.

38:30.354 --> 38:33.161
It's Alfred Hitchcock
in a rented toupee.

38:33.186 --> 38:34.775
[Laughs] C'mon.

38:34.800 --> 38:36.399
Why would you rent a toupee?

38:36.424 --> 38:37.883
Y'know, from the Toupee Store.

38:37.908 --> 38:41.103
- So you don't have to maintain it.
- [Chuckles]

38:42.787 --> 38:45.279
- All right. Seven and Seven.
- Yeah.

38:45.304 --> 38:46.685
And an Old Fashioned.

38:46.710 --> 38:48.492
Keep 'em coming, good sir.

38:48.517 --> 38:50.661
Uh, oh. [Clears throat]

38:50.686 --> 38:53.612
Can you, uh, start charging this card

38:53.637 --> 38:55.583
- instead of that other one?
- Yeah, yeah. You got it.

38:55.608 --> 38:57.388
- Thank you. [Sniffles]
- No problem.

38:57.415 --> 39:00.350
You're not maxing out
your cards, are you?

39:00.352 --> 39:02.259
Of course not.

39:02.284 --> 39:05.475
I'm, um, spreading the points around.

39:05.500 --> 39:07.085
- I got a system.
- Oh.

39:07.110 --> 39:08.899
[Inhales sharply, sighs]

39:08.924 --> 39:12.059
- That moron takes the bet.
- [Clears throat]

39:12.084 --> 39:14.507
He took 3 points. He's a fool.

39:14.509 --> 39:16.343
Look, is it wrong...

39:16.345 --> 39:19.108
Whoa. Hey, hey, this guy over here.

39:19.133 --> 39:20.513
[Inhales sharply]

39:20.515 --> 39:24.195
Yeah, he wants everyone to
know what a big spender he is.

39:24.220 --> 39:27.650
I got every dollar the guy owns.

39:27.675 --> 39:30.153
We're here to meet a celebrity

39:30.178 --> 39:31.963
who's donating to my charity.

39:31.988 --> 39:33.321
Kevin Costner.

39:33.346 --> 39:36.173
I-I will go stand in that corner.

39:36.198 --> 39:38.135
You point me out...

39:38.160 --> 39:40.333
you're meeting Kevin Costner.

39:40.358 --> 39:42.826
What? You don't look like Kevin Costner.

39:42.851 --> 39:44.975
Uh... I look exactly like Kevin Costner.

39:45.000 --> 39:46.266
People are always coming up to me,

39:46.291 --> 39:48.625
saying they loved me in "Bull Durham."

39:48.650 --> 39:50.896
Never. Never happened.

39:50.921 --> 39:52.097
- Always.
- No, not once.

39:52.099 --> 39:53.709
- [Snapping fingers] Hey! Hey, you!
- Waiter: Yes, sir?

39:53.734 --> 39:56.251
- What is this?
- Uh, dirty Martini?

39:56.276 --> 39:59.081
No, this is a $14 glass of puke.

39:59.106 --> 40:01.242
Why don't you get that
idiot look off your face

40:01.267 --> 40:02.733
and get me another one?

40:02.758 --> 40:04.697
- That guy.
- Who said anything about gin?

40:04.722 --> 40:07.788
- How do we get him?
- Well, I want vodka.

40:07.813 --> 40:09.845
- [Inhales sharply]
- W-what am I just gonna hold it here?

40:09.870 --> 40:12.327
- What do you think?
- You go and get me another one.

40:12.352 --> 40:15.383
The... the trick with the
coin you told me about?

40:15.408 --> 40:17.041
I know your boss. I'm an investor here.

40:17.066 --> 40:18.499
- Or the counterfeit bill?
- No.

40:18.524 --> 40:20.090
I know your boss, and
I know your boss' boss.

40:20.115 --> 40:21.615
That guy's a real asshole.

40:21.640 --> 40:23.395
... Act together and
get me a real drink.

40:23.420 --> 40:25.574
He needs to go down. Hard.

40:25.599 --> 40:27.657
What kind of menial job is this?

40:27.682 --> 40:29.328
♪ ♪

40:29.353 --> 40:31.086
Here's what we're gonna do.

40:31.111 --> 40:33.256
We're gonna sell him
a worthless credit card

40:33.281 --> 40:35.818
for 5,000 bucks.

40:36.329 --> 40:38.530
[Chuckling] Here's what you do.

40:38.555 --> 40:41.234
Make eye contact with him.

40:41.259 --> 40:44.445
That's all it'll take for him
to think you're interested.

40:44.470 --> 40:47.571
I'll act good and drunk,
and he'll think I'm a loser

40:47.596 --> 40:49.320
and try to steal you away.

40:49.345 --> 40:52.223
He will persist.

40:52.829 --> 40:54.229
Mm.

40:54.254 --> 40:56.815
Tell him you can't
leave me. Not... not yet.

40:56.840 --> 40:59.402
Let him know you're trying
to roll me. [Inhales sharply]

40:59.427 --> 41:01.225
He'll want in.

41:01.250 --> 41:03.980
He'll help you ply me with booze.

41:04.005 --> 41:06.249
Then you take my wallet.
You lift the card.

41:06.274 --> 41:08.334
Following this?

41:09.602 --> 41:12.327
We're not actually doing this, right?

41:12.947 --> 41:14.905
We're just talking?

41:14.930 --> 41:17.250
♪ ♪

41:17.275 --> 41:19.081
Yeah.

41:19.619 --> 41:21.633
[Chuckling] Just talkin'.

41:21.665 --> 41:22.964
[Sighs]

41:22.989 --> 41:26.224
♪ ♪

41:27.968 --> 41:29.797
What?

41:29.822 --> 41:32.171
♪ ♪

41:32.196 --> 41:34.176
Nothing.

41:34.201 --> 41:35.756
It's not nothing. What?

41:35.781 --> 41:37.518
I keep thinking...

41:40.583 --> 41:43.365
was there another way?

41:43.395 --> 41:45.652
[Chuckling] Another way?

41:46.414 --> 41:49.181
W... Chuck? Is that what
you're talking about?

41:49.183 --> 41:52.579
Kim... he had us in a corner, okay?

41:52.604 --> 41:55.661
- We did what we had to do.
- But Rebecca...

41:55.686 --> 41:59.176
Everything that happened
was his own fault.

41:59.201 --> 42:00.533
Everything.

42:00.558 --> 42:02.558
And put him in the rear-view mirror.

42:02.583 --> 42:04.383
He is not worth thinkin' about.

42:04.408 --> 42:05.741
Done.

42:05.766 --> 42:10.168
♪ ♪

42:11.416 --> 42:13.326
Woman: Why, thank you.

42:13.351 --> 42:15.374
Have a good evening.

42:16.535 --> 42:18.201
[Sighs]

42:18.226 --> 42:23.465
[Indistinct conversations,
glasses clinking]

42:26.750 --> 42:31.353
[Planet E's <i> "Klub Kola"</i> plays]

42:31.390 --> 42:33.525
How about that one?

42:34.819 --> 42:37.874
♪ ♪

42:37.899 --> 42:40.500
I bet we could get him to...

42:40.525 --> 42:45.361
invest in some of Giselle St.
Claire's land in South Africa.

42:45.386 --> 42:48.177
Oh, yeah. Definitely.

42:48.202 --> 42:49.454
[Sighs]

42:49.479 --> 42:51.859
The mining rights would be all his.

42:51.884 --> 42:55.147
♪ ♪

42:55.747 --> 42:58.601
[Insects chirping]

43:01.058 --> 43:03.358
[Gearshift clicks]

43:05.110 --> 43:07.680
- [Engine shuts off]
- [Keys jingle]

43:07.705 --> 43:11.073
[Wind whistling]

43:21.724 --> 43:23.355
[Sighs]

43:25.380 --> 43:26.871
Really?

43:27.318 --> 43:30.306
He called me. For obvious reasons.

43:30.331 --> 43:32.756
Look, I'm not here to rip him off.

43:32.781 --> 43:35.234
He has the stuff, right?

43:35.259 --> 43:38.094
I need to know what you're planning.

43:38.119 --> 43:39.952
What's it matter to you?

43:39.977 --> 43:42.044
I know they're for Salamanca.

43:42.069 --> 43:43.560
Nitro pills.

43:43.585 --> 43:45.744
Your boss has heart problems.

43:45.769 --> 43:48.908
You already got it all
figured out, why're you asking?

43:49.439 --> 43:52.172
How you gonna make the switch?

43:53.572 --> 43:55.005
[Sighs]

43:55.030 --> 43:57.015
Hector keeps the pills
in his coat pocket.

43:57.040 --> 43:59.992
When he hangs up his
coat, I'll make the switch.

44:00.600 --> 44:03.819
Mm. He goes down. Then what?

44:03.821 --> 44:06.488
His heart goes out. That's it.

44:06.490 --> 44:08.682
A lot of eyes on Salamanca.

44:08.707 --> 44:11.269
You do this, how are you gonna stop them

44:11.294 --> 44:13.552
from finding out it was you?

44:15.166 --> 44:17.632
Are you tryin' to
tell me not to do this?

44:17.657 --> 44:19.912
I'm not tellin' you anything.

44:19.937 --> 44:22.597
Just want to make sure you
know what you're getting into.

44:22.622 --> 44:25.887
I'm not getting into
anything. I'm in it.

44:25.912 --> 44:28.100
I've got no choice.

44:31.178 --> 44:32.544
[Sighs]

44:32.569 --> 44:34.732
Hector wants to use my dad's business.

44:34.757 --> 44:37.224
My dad is a straight arrow.
He won't stand for it,

44:37.249 --> 44:39.525
which means he goes to the police,

44:39.550 --> 44:42.215
which means he's a dead man.

44:43.128 --> 44:45.638
And that's not happening.

44:45.663 --> 44:48.057
You get caught, it could get worse.

44:48.082 --> 44:50.498
You don't think I know
who I'm dealing with?

44:50.501 --> 44:51.982
No.

44:52.007 --> 44:53.526
I don't.

45:09.956 --> 45:11.723
[Gas cap rattling]

45:11.748 --> 45:13.479
What are you doing?

45:24.875 --> 45:28.475
[Gas cap rattling]

45:28.500 --> 45:29.985
[Gas-cap door closes]

45:33.876 --> 45:36.076
There are more people
than the Salamancas

45:36.101 --> 45:37.979
to worry about here.

45:38.004 --> 45:39.889
Now, if you manage to pull this off

45:39.914 --> 45:43.952
without a bullet in your
head and switch those pills,

45:43.977 --> 45:45.988
then switch 'em back.

45:47.558 --> 45:49.447
Switch them back?

45:49.472 --> 45:50.784
Why?

45:50.809 --> 45:53.630
Anyone gets an itch about
the medicine not working,

45:53.655 --> 45:55.870
they're gonna look at those pills.

45:55.895 --> 45:57.328
You do this...

45:57.353 --> 45:59.160
switch 'em back.

46:04.140 --> 46:07.111
So... you gonna let us make this deal?

46:07.136 --> 46:08.821
You got the money?

46:11.408 --> 46:12.789
Good.

46:12.814 --> 46:14.193
[Sniffles]

46:14.218 --> 46:17.068
Now, before we do this...

46:17.093 --> 46:20.176
I'm gonna need one more thing from you.

46:23.342 --> 46:26.476
- [Indistinct conversations]
- _

46:26.501 --> 46:28.448
[Intercom beeps]

46:29.253 --> 46:31.120
Yes?

46:31.145 --> 46:32.597
Okay.

46:33.187 --> 46:35.662
Miss Valco will see you now.

46:35.919 --> 46:38.040
- Oh.
- Second door.

46:42.385 --> 46:45.618
[Breathes sharply]

46:46.350 --> 46:48.118
Hi there. Come on in.

46:48.143 --> 46:52.287
Yeah. Hi. I've...
called quite a few times

46:52.289 --> 46:55.019
about an issue I'm trying to address.

46:55.044 --> 46:57.250
Do you have your policy number?

46:57.275 --> 46:58.555
No.

46:58.580 --> 46:59.717
[Sighs]

46:59.742 --> 47:02.702
Can you just look up my name? McGill?

47:07.124 --> 47:10.566
Charles McGill of
Hamlin, Hamlin, McGill?

47:11.469 --> 47:13.141
No, that's my brother.

47:13.143 --> 47:14.376
Um... [Clears throat]

47:14.378 --> 47:16.886
I'm Jimmy. James McGill.

47:16.911 --> 47:18.926
Solo practitioner.

47:19.923 --> 47:21.934
Oh. There you are.

47:21.959 --> 47:24.368
Looks like you're all
paid up through the year.

47:24.393 --> 47:26.226
That's sort of the issue.

47:26.251 --> 47:30.063
Long story short, through a
series of unfortunate events,

47:30.088 --> 47:32.328
my license has been suspended.

47:32.353 --> 47:34.203
Yes, I see that here.

47:34.228 --> 47:35.679
Right. Well...

47:35.704 --> 47:37.504
I was hoping I could get a refund

47:37.529 --> 47:39.056
for the time that I won't be a lawyer.

47:39.081 --> 47:41.513
Now, that's only fair, right?

47:41.538 --> 47:44.286
I'm sorry, Mr. McGill.
It doesn't work like that.

47:44.311 --> 47:47.916
We don't refund for unused
malpractice insurance.

47:47.941 --> 47:49.183
[Sighs] But it's a...

47:49.208 --> 47:51.990
it's a lot of money for nothing.

47:52.015 --> 47:53.906
I understand it seems that way,

47:53.931 --> 47:55.564
but if one of your clients decides

47:55.589 --> 47:57.855
they want to bring a suit against you,

47:57.880 --> 48:00.242
this continues your coverage.

48:00.267 --> 48:01.590
[Snaps fingers] That's the thing.

48:01.592 --> 48:03.159
My clients?

48:03.184 --> 48:04.583
They love me.

48:04.608 --> 48:07.612
And they would never
bring a suit against me.

48:07.637 --> 48:10.234
I'm [Chuckling] extremely lovable.

48:10.259 --> 48:11.831
I can see that.

48:11.856 --> 48:14.557
But it's company policy.

48:14.942 --> 48:16.440
[Snaps fingers]

48:16.465 --> 48:18.999
What about we put the insurance on hold?

48:19.024 --> 48:21.138
And then, if someone
were to try to sue me...

48:21.163 --> 48:22.587
which they won't...

48:22.612 --> 48:24.089
then we just, uh, [Clicks tongue]

48:24.091 --> 48:26.432
kick that ol' policy back into gear?

48:26.457 --> 48:29.296
I understand your situation. I do.

48:29.321 --> 48:31.114
But there are rules preventing us

48:31.139 --> 48:33.765
from stopping and starting coverage.

48:33.791 --> 48:36.684
And I regret to inform you that...

48:36.709 --> 48:39.361
when your license is
reinstated next year,

48:39.363 --> 48:40.529
because of the suspension,

48:40.554 --> 48:43.409
your premiums are going to... go up.

48:43.434 --> 48:45.381
Considerably.

48:46.500 --> 48:48.680
How considerably?

48:49.642 --> 48:52.022
Um... [Drawer opens]

48:54.945 --> 49:00.982
Looks like roughly... 150%.

49:03.484 --> 49:05.540
[Breathing sharply]

49:05.565 --> 49:07.171
[Chuckling] God.

49:08.777 --> 49:11.171
[Sniffling]

49:11.196 --> 49:13.363
[Drawer closes]

49:14.810 --> 49:16.498
Mr. McGill?

49:16.500 --> 49:18.439
[Sighs]

49:19.837 --> 49:21.581
[Sniffles]

49:23.618 --> 49:25.635
Oh.

49:25.660 --> 49:26.926
I...

49:26.951 --> 49:29.054
Mr. McGill, I'm sorry.

49:29.079 --> 49:31.913
I wish we could help
you, but we just can't.

49:31.915 --> 49:33.474
[Sniffles]

49:33.499 --> 49:35.244
I'm sorry.

49:37.142 --> 49:38.875
It's hard.

49:39.354 --> 49:41.656
Very, very hard.

49:41.658 --> 49:42.853
[Sniffles]

49:42.878 --> 49:45.509
I'm just having a rough time.

49:46.529 --> 49:48.846
I just need a break.

49:48.871 --> 49:51.455
[Voice breaking] Just one break.

49:53.317 --> 49:57.445
And I know you... I know
you can't do anything, but...

49:57.618 --> 49:59.571
[Crying]

49:59.596 --> 50:03.747
I'm getting run out on this
community service and...

50:03.772 --> 50:07.045
getting ripped off
left and right, and...

50:07.453 --> 50:09.353
my car won't start.

50:09.378 --> 50:11.119
[Chuckles]

50:11.144 --> 50:14.242
My gal is disappointed in me, and...

50:14.267 --> 50:16.335
my brother...

50:16.360 --> 50:17.776
[Sniffles]

50:17.801 --> 50:19.233
[Crying]

50:19.258 --> 50:21.499
My brother is sick!

50:22.381 --> 50:24.433
And he's alone.

50:26.803 --> 50:29.546
I spent years caring for him, and...

50:29.571 --> 50:31.306
now he hates me.

50:31.308 --> 50:33.877
He's the only family I got left,

50:33.902 --> 50:35.778
and he hates me.

50:35.803 --> 50:38.082
He hates my guts.

50:38.107 --> 50:40.606
Is this your brother, Charles?

50:40.631 --> 50:42.412
- Oh.
- [Sniffles]

50:42.437 --> 50:45.738
And I pretend not to
care, but he's my brother.

50:45.763 --> 50:47.633
How can I not?

50:47.658 --> 50:50.241
He's mentally ill.

50:50.266 --> 50:53.862
He's... he's holed up in
a house with no electricity.

50:53.864 --> 50:56.585
He's working by the
light of gas lanterns.

50:56.610 --> 50:57.909
Wha...

50:57.934 --> 51:01.031
He's making mistakes
with his clients. He's...

51:01.056 --> 51:03.868
mixin' up numbers on
important documents.

51:03.893 --> 51:05.466
He... he...

51:06.480 --> 51:08.848
He had a complete mental breakdown

51:08.873 --> 51:10.606
at the bar hearing.

51:10.631 --> 51:14.233
Your brother... he had
a breakdown in court?

51:14.258 --> 51:16.724
It's in the transcripts.

51:16.749 --> 51:18.278
[Sobbing]

51:18.303 --> 51:21.104
God. And I'm worried, I'm just...

51:21.129 --> 51:25.162
if he screws up with
one more big client...

51:26.240 --> 51:29.033
it's just gonna destroy him!

51:30.071 --> 51:31.604
[Sniffles]

51:31.629 --> 51:34.596
Oh, don't... don't write...

51:34.621 --> 51:36.707
What are you writing? No, don't write.

51:36.732 --> 51:38.920
I-I didn't mean to say that.

51:38.945 --> 51:41.646
I don't want him to get
in trouble with you guys

51:41.671 --> 51:43.971
- 'cause of me. I...
- Right.

51:43.996 --> 51:46.863
I'm sorry. I'm gonna go.

51:47.662 --> 51:50.251
You're not gonna do anything, are you?

51:50.253 --> 51:52.861
I-I wouldn't worry about it, Mr. McGill.

51:52.886 --> 51:54.786
Uh, please feel better.

51:54.811 --> 51:56.594
I'm sorry.

